Woohoo! The newest book by Calligrafile founder, Molly Suber Thorpe (@plurabellestudio – author of Modern Calligraphy) is out! It's available now, internationally, in both print and eBook formats. Visit calligrafile.com/handbook to find out where to buy it (live 🔗 in profile).
📘📖 The Calligrapher's Business Handbook is a guide to best business practices and pricing strategies for calligraphers and lettering artists. Whether you’re starting out in creative freelancing, transitioning from a different profession, or running a lettering business that just needs a boost, you will welcome the invaluable ideas in this handbook. Molly has packed these pages with a range of topics for freelance calligraphers and hand lettering artists, including:
• How professional calligraphers charge for their services
• Whether to charge flat rates or hourly rates
• When – and how – to offer discounts or freebies
• How to charge for commercial work, such as logo designs
• How to get the most bang for your advertising budget • What goes into a fair project contract
• How to navigate copyright licensing and know your rights!
___
Find out where to buy it near you at calligrafile.com/handbook. Live 🔗 in profile.

Pricing - Marty turns in getting ready to rope another - 
Pricing isn't easy starting out, you may end up changing your rates a dozen different times...or just copying someone else's.  As you'll find, pricing is more about you than it is a product or service.  You must price in such a way that you cover your expenses AND yourself.  What your time is worth is very subjective.  Your expenses are typically fixed, among the many are: annual website cost, your cost to print an image, gas for your car, insurance for your business (and car), capital investment in equipment, does this all make sense?  Then include what you're time is worth (minimum wage??) What you'll find is that some will charge a one time fee for everything, others include a fee and price prints/digitals and accessories separately.  The biggest piece of advice that I could give anyone just starting, stick with it, I know it's discouraging when people say "you're too expensive" but...a rising tide lifts all boats!  Think that $800 per participant for a two day workshop is expensive, play the numbers out...you're barely breaking even.  Trust me that workshops are primarily out there because people love to share with others.  Stick with it...not every roper makes every catch.
